<div id="alexia-akbay" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="business-tech food-farming ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--alexia-akbay" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Alexia Akbay</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>COFOUNDER &amp; CEO, SYMBROSIA<br />
KAILUA-KONA, HAWAII</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>She&#8217;s working on a cure for the bovine belch</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/alexia-akbay-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/alexia-akbay-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/alexia-akbay-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/alexia-akbay-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/alexia-akbay-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>In the brownish-reddish fronds of red algae, Alexia Akbay sees the future, and it looks something like Beano for cows. Bovine guts produce methane, a powerful greenhouse gas, but the humble seaweed <em>Asparagopsis taxiformis</em> reduces the output by up to 85 percent when used as a dietary supplement.</p>
<p>Akbay founded Symbrosia while in grad school at Yale to see if the seaweed could be grown at scale and plugged into a sustainable circular-economy model. The company is currently growing happy, healthy seaweed, fertilized by poop from a neighboring shrimp farm, in 1,500-liter commercial-sized tanks. A proof-of-concept demo is slated for this June, with an eye toward a commercial product in early 2022. Livestock produce up to 10 percent of global greenhouse emissions, and while Bessie might not be as sexy as a Tesla, says Akbay, “we think livestock is just opening up as a potential industry for emission reductions.”</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/AlexiaAkbay" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Alexia Akbay</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
