<div id="erika-dickerson-despenza" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="arts-media ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--erika-dickerson-despenza" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Erika Dickerson-Despenza</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>RADICAL BLACK FEMINIST CULTURAL WORKER AND PLAYWRIGHT<br />
CHICAGO, ILLINOIS</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>This playwright puts justice in the spotlight</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/erika-dickerson-despenza-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/erika-dickerson-despenza-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/erika-dickerson-despenza-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/erika-dickerson-despenza-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/erika-dickerson-despenza-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
									<p class="g50-profile__photo-credit">Photo: Joey Stocks</p>
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>The concept of justice, and who benefits from it, preoccupies Erika Dickerson-Despenza. She describes herself as a radical black feminist and cultural worker, and sees her playwriting as a form of organizing. In 2016–2017, as curriculum specialist for social-justice arts org People’s Theatre Project, her goal was to teach young people how to engage their communities both politically and socially, and to become, in essence, community organizers.</p>
<p>Now, as Tow Playwright-in-Residence at New York’s prestigious Public Theater, Dickerson-Despenza’s goals are heading for a larger stage. Her upcoming play, <em>cullud wattah</em>, uses the Flint water crisis as a backdrop for a black family in turmoil. It’s set to open in July. She’s also curating a series of “public chats,” like videos and podcasts, featuring people struggling with other water crises, and is writing a 10-play cycle about Hurricane Katrina. The common theme, she says: “How do we abolish systems and circumstances that allow such apocalyptic moments to happen?”</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/blkplaywright" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Erika Dickerson-Despenza</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
		<div class="g50-profile__categories">
			<span>Category: </span>
												<button data-category="arts-media">
						Arts &amp; Media					</button>
																</div>

		<div class="g50-profile__footer">
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-mobile">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/blkplaywright" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Erika Dickerson-Despenza</a>			</div>

