<div id="hillel-echo-hawk" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="food-farming ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--hillel-echo-hawk" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Hillel Echo-Hawk</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>CHEF &amp; OWNER, BIRCH BASKET<br />
SEATTLE, WASHINGTON</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>This chef’s dinners will also feed your mind</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/hillel-echo-hawk-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/hillel-echo-hawk-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/hillel-echo-hawk-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/hillel-echo-hawk-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/hillel-echo-hawk-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>Growing up in rural Alaska, Hillel Echo-Hawk drew inspiration from a nearby Athabaskan matriarch who fought the state government for decades over subsistence hunting and fishing rights for her people. Echo-Hawk, who is Pawnee and Athabaskan, learned from her how to live off the land — and how to fight for what you believe in. Echo-Hawk trained as a chef, and launched her own catering company two years ago that focuses on indigenous foods with an original twist. Think: not just corn and squash, but also duck-fat maple popcorn.</p>
<p>In her hands, food, the ultimate human connector, is also education. At catered dinners, she’ll tell attendees why she makes certain dishes, why she chooses certain ingredients — the story behind the meal. “When I say these things, and put down a plate of food, the lightbulb goes off, and people have a new understanding about native people,” she says. Then comes her greatest pleasure: walking around, listening to what people are saying about the meal, and joining the conversation.</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://www.instagram.com/birchbasket/" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-instagram g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Hillel Echo-Hawk</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
		<div class="g50-profile__categories">
			<span>Category: </span>
												<button data-category="food-farming">
						Food &amp; Farming					</button>
																</div>

		<div class="g50-profile__footer">
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-mobile">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://www.instagram.com/birchbasket/" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-instagram g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Hillel Echo-Hawk</a>			</div>

