<div id="wanjiku-wawa-gatheru" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="food-farming ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--wanjiku-wawa-gatheru" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Wanjiku “Wawa” Gatheru</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>STUDENT, UNIVERSITY OF CONNECTICUT<br />
POMFRET, CONNECTICUT</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>She&#8217;s shaping food policy — and she&#8217;s still an undergrad</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/wanjiku-e2809cwawae2809d-gatheru-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/wanjiku-e2809cwawae2809d-gatheru-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/wanjiku-e2809cwawae2809d-gatheru-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/wanjiku-e2809cwawae2809d-gatheru-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/wanjiku-e2809cwawae2809d-gatheru-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
									<p class="g50-profile__photo-credit">Photo: Xingyi Chen</p>
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>In high school, Wawa Gatheru became interested in environmental justice. Growing up in a rural and predominantly white town in Connecticut, Gatheru — the daughter of Kenyan immigrants — wanted to explore the role of racism in climate. For her final project, she researched the geographic overlaps between events such as police brutality against black people and the locations of toxic waste sites or fossil fuel infrastructure. She saw a trend, and noticed barely anyone was talking about it. “I was really frustrated, because I was getting all this information, but the conversations just weren’t being had in the community,” she says.</p>
<p>As a college senior, she cofounded the UConn Access to Food Effort (UCAFE), a campus initiative that helped launch the first assessment of food insecurity at the university. Soon she’ll be off to the University of Oxford as UConn’s first Rhodes Scholar. She plans to pursue a master&#8217;s degree in environment and political science, and hopes to run for Congress someday. “We need people who are representing us who understand that climate embodies everything,” she says.</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/wawagatheru" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Wawa Gatheru</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
		<div class="g50-profile__categories">
			<span>Category: </span>
												<button data-category="food-farming">
						Food &amp; Farming					</button>
																</div>

		<div class="g50-profile__footer">
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-mobile">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/wawagatheru" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Wawa Gatheru</a>			</div>

