<div id="tim-latimer" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="business-tech climate-energy ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--tim-latimer" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Tim Latimer</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>COFOUNDER &amp; CEO, FERVO ENERGY<br />
HOUSTON, TEXAS</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>His plans for geothermal energy are really heating up</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/tim-latimer-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/tim-latimer-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/tim-latimer-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/tim-latimer-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/tim-latimer-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>As a drilling engineer, Tim Latimer pumped oil and gas out of the ground with cutting-edge technology that he knew would only make climate change worse. “I had one skill, which was poking deep holes into the ground,” Latimer says. Then he had a realization: That skill could be adapted to clean energy in the form of geothermal power, which taps into the Earth’s natural underground heat and steam to generate electricity.</p>
<p>In 2017, he cofounded Fervo, planning to apply new methods of horizontal drilling and fiber-optic-sensing techniques to locate and use geothermal hotspots. The company plans to launch a clean energy project by 2021.</p>
<p>Latimer hopes that geothermal will someday produce 20 percent of U.S. electricity (it generates a scant 0.5 percent today). It has a long track record of safety, he says, and unlike solar or wind, it’s not dependent on weather or season. “We can be that missing piece of the puzzle to get us to a completely clean grid,” he says.</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/timmlatimer" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Tim Latimer</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
		<div class="g50-profile__categories">
			<span>Category: </span>
												<button data-category="business-tech">
						Business &amp; Tech					</button>
																<button data-category="climate-energy">
						Climate &amp; Energy					</button>
																</div>

		<div class="g50-profile__footer">
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-mobile">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/timmlatimer" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Tim Latimer</a>			</div>

