<div id="catrina-rorke" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="climate-energy policy-advocacy ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--catrina-rorke" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Catrina Rorke</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>VP, CLIMATE LEADERSHIP COUNCIL<br />
WASHINGTON, D.C.</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>Want to burn fossil fuels? She’ll make you pay</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/catrina-rorke-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/catrina-rorke-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/catrina-rorke-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/catrina-rorke-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/catrina-rorke-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>When Catrina Rorke first joined former U.S. Representative Bob Inglis as a fellow on a six-month rotation, she “didn’t understand a lick of [politics],” she says, laughing. But she caught on quick and wound up sticking with Inglis for two more years, writing the first Republican-sponsored carbon tax bill — a policy that would make polluters pay for burning carbon-emitting fuels.</p>
<p>The bill failed and Inglis was later voted out. But something clicked for Rorke, who has dedicated her career to making carbon-pricing policy real. She sees it as the most straightforward way to reduce emissions. “If you price something, you get less of it,” Rorke says — plain and simple.</p>
<p>Now, Rorke and her team at the Climate Leadership Council advocate for carbon dividends, which would be distributed to the taxpayers who ultimately bear the cost of a carbon tax. Because the CLC is backed by oil companies and recommends regulatory rollbacks, some environmentalists distrust the plan. But, says Rorke, it enables individual choice to address a problem that affects everyone. “We&#8217;re all stakeholders in the same climate,” Rorke says. “We want households to be best equipped to make the right decisions for themselves.”</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/crorke" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Catrina Rorke</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
