<div id="gloria-walton" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="policy-advocacy ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--gloria-walton" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Gloria Walton</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>PRESIDENT &amp; CEO, SCOPE<br />
LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>In South Central, she’s shaping policy for the people</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/gloria-walton-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/gloria-walton-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/gloria-walton-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/gloria-walton-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/gloria-walton-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>Growing up in a household of minimal means in Jackson, Mississippi, Gloria Walton had her sights set on law school and the “traditional” path to success. At UCLA, a class on U.S. grassroots protest movements knocked her off that path and into an internship at community-organizing nonprofit SCOPE (Strategic Concepts in Organizing and Policy Education), in South Central L.A. There, Walton learned that she could be part of the decision-making processes that shape the lives of South Central’s 900,000-odd residents.</p>
<p>Today, 15 years later, she’s SCOPE’s president and CEO, orchestrating a new climate agenda for the nonprofit by investing in community-led plans that tweak policy levers. One plan diverted millions from a state/local cap-and-trade bill to a fund benefiting regions bearing the brunt of the climate crisis. SCOPE was also involved in the creation of the nation’s first climate-emergency mobilization office, which will be advised by indigenous and frontline residents. Cities tend to invest more in neighborhoods as they gentrify, Walton says, “but they should invest in the communities that are there now.”</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/SCOPE_LA" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow SCOPE</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
		<div class="g50-profile__categories">
			<span>Category: </span>
																			<button data-category="policy-advocacy">
						Policy &amp; Advocacy					</button>
									</div>

		<div class="g50-profile__footer">
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-mobile">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://twitter.com/SCOPE_LA" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow SCOPE</a>			</div>

