<div id="courtney-williams" class="js-filtered-profile g50-profile-container" data-category-list="policy-advocacy ">

	
	<div class="g50-profile g50-profile--courtney-williams" >

		<!-- label (like for sponsors) -->
		
		<!-- person's name -->
		<h2 class="g50-profile__name">
			<span>Courtney Williams</span>
		</h2>

		<!-- person's position & city -->
					<div class="g50-profile__stats"><p>CHIEF STRATEGIST, THE BROWN BIKE GIRL<br />
BROOKLYN, NEW YORK</p>
</div>
		
		<!-- person's excerpt -->
		<h3 class="g50-profile__excerpt"><p>She&#8217;s a spokes-person for more inclusive transit</p>
</h3>

		<!-- guest author stuff -->
		
		<!-- person's photo -->
					<div class="g50-profile__photo">
				<img src="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/courtney-williams-1.jpg?w=560" class="g50-profile__photo-img wp-post-image" alt="" data-noattr="1" srcset="https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/courtney-williams-1.jpg?w=560 560w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/courtney-williams-1.jpg?w=1120 1120w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/courtney-williams-1.jpg?w=330 330w, https://grist.files.wordpress.com/2020/03/courtney-williams-1.jpg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 560px) 100vw, 560px" />				<!-- photo credit -->
							</div>
		
		<!-- person's content -->
		<div class="g50-profile__body">
			<p>As a kid growing up in Gary, Indiana, Courtney Williams loved riding bikes. But it wasn’t until she moved to New York City, at the height of <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/30/fashion/30BICYCLE.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">cycle chic</a>, that she found her calling on two wheels: bringing more people of color into the bike community.</p>
<p>Williams organized a group of black women to ride together, eventually founding a one-woman bicycle-advocacy consulting business called The Brown Bike Girl. The name, she says, reflects how she often felt — like “the <em>one</em> brown person in a room with these other cycling advocates.”</p>
<p>She’s now trained a dozen other leaders to spread the bike gospel and plan rides of their own that are exciting, inclusive, and safe. In 2020, Williams plans to tackle another accessibility issue: language. Misunderstanding a road sign could put her neighbors in harm’s way, so she wants to develop and teach bike-safety vocabulary in other languages, starting this year with Spanish and a dialect of Chinese. “I’m a forward-motion person,” Williams says. “That’s really the only direction bikes go.”</p>
			<div class="g50-follow g50-follow--hide-desktop">
				<a class="g50-follow__link" href="https://www.instagram.com/thebrownbikegirl" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-instagram g50-follow__icon"></i>Follow Courtney Williams</a>			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- person's cagetgories -->
